<p>Hi Emil,</p>
<p>When you bookmark something using a standard tool, it’s treated as a link. It appears in a list with all your other links, which all look the same.</p>
<p>That’s not the case with mymind.</p>
<p>Your mind automatically analyzes and categorizes everything you save. Every URL appears differently with its own visual card, so you can tell what it is at a glance.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qyn-B1ZloPY" style="color: #FF5924;">▶️ <strong>See how Smart Bookmarking works [Video]</strong></a></p>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Save a product?</strong> mymind knows it’s a product and saves the proper image and price. It even knows the brand or designer of the product you saved, so you can search “shoes” or “nike” or “off-white” to find it later.</p>
<img src="https://carbon-media.accelerator.net/00000000001/dgTUJkjd6Qig4szjlBvEKe;870x540.png?auto=webp" width="960" height="463" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;"/>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Save an article or recipe?</strong> With <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=in5mKkJvELQ" style="color: #FF5924;"><strong>Reading Mode,</strong></a> mymind strips away the clutter, ads and other distractions, leaving you with a clean view you can read in peace.</p>
<img src="https://carbon-media.accelerator.net/00000000001/6giyI6Dhvf4dUHYCVOMJHD;872x540.png?auto=webp" width="960" height="463" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;"/>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Save a movie or TV series?</strong> mymind knows what it is and saves the film or series poster, along with the rating, summary and other relevant details you can search and review later.</p>
<img src="https://carbon-media.accelerator.net/00000000001/kYyvQs78bVvbMU3ecxawhM;870x540.png?auto=webp" width="960" height="463" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;"/>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Save a book?</strong> mymind automatically recognizes and categorizes it as a book for you. Even better, it shows up with its own beautiful book card, so you can easily browse and spot it in your mind.</p>
<img src="https://carbon-media.accelerator.net/00000000001/luA22LhNBmObfcUvrA1fjF;872x540.png?auto=webp" width="960" height="463" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;"/>
<p> </p>
<p><strong>Save a tweet?</strong> mymind knows it’s a tweet and saves at as one for you, with its own special preview.</p>
<img src="https://carbon-media.accelerator.net/00000000001/0DYCis5ZGtTeAk1rHyFmZn;872x540.png?auto=webp" width="960" height="463" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;"/>
<p> </p>
<p>Try saving videos, real estate properties, Wikipedia pages. They’ll all appear differently in your mind, with their uniquely relevant information. You didn’t organize these URLS, categorize them, tag them, title them or stop to think about them at all beyond hitting save. mymind did it all for you.</p>
<img src="https://carbon-media.accelerator.net/00000000001/95PWccN84Zvc5VlcA3g8LG;870x540.png?auto=webp" width="960" height="463" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;"/>
<p>Just like complex machinations of your real brain, constantly working behind the scenes without your conscious knowledge, you might not even notice mymind’s magic.</p>
<p>If it’s doing its job well, it feels like it <em>just works.</em></p>
